“I just feel really confident when I play football because that’s something that I struggle with a little bit” Bianca says. “But when I play football I feel like I can do anything.”⁣⁣Bianca had football dreams but not many options to play. Until @hackneywickfc started in 2015 and soon after started a women’s program which she joined. The club has grown from one men’s side to now serving hundreds of people in the East London borough. Bianca has become a success story of the club and now also plays for Tottenham’s junior side.⁣⁣Watch Episode 1 of our new series “From the Grounds Up” about the people creating community change through @Nikefootball on IGTV.

⠀ ⠀ From local streets to global stages these athletes are defining a collective legacy finding personal truth and generational progress through the power of sport and culture. ⠀Check out professional ballet dancer at the Dance Theater of Harlem @ingridsilva and media personality and advocate @scottiebeam in a conversation about making moves toward the future they believe in. #bhm #untilweallwin

“We talk a lot about gender equality about how important it is for girls and women to have empowerment and that they earn their space” says Júlia Vergueiro co-founder of Pelado Real Football Club the only private all-girls football club in São Paulo. “Football can be a big tool for that because a girl who earns a place on the field believes she can also have a place in her family at work or wherever she is.” ⠀Support for women’s football has grown globally since last summer’s tournament and in Brazil where it was broadcast for the first time on national television the shift has been strong. In the months following a new attendance record was set for professional club football and Júlia says at her own club enrollments and participation have doubled.This is Ripple Effect. See our Story for the full film.

“I work as a doctor in a very busy hospital in London. It's extremely stressful and busy — I'm up on my feet all the time so swimming is a way for me to escape that busy lifestyle and reality. And it just gives me a feeling of weightlessness.” ⠀@gazawiyaaa is a Palestinian scuba diver and swimmer who lives and works in London. Shop the link in bio.

“Yoga by definition is this idea of union and that’s not just happening in your own body; but helping you create more positive and less harmful relationships with the people around you. When we think about how quickly yoga is growing the only way that we make this accessible is for all of us to show up as a team. Not just for ourselves but for each other — so that everybody feels like this practice is for them.”⠀@nicoleacardoza has committed her life to reducing the wellness gap by bringing yoga to everyone regardless of background resources or age. Her program Yoga Foster is a national nonprofit that empowers educators with yoga and mindfulness resources for the classroom.

“For me impossible is a word that only exists in other people’s minds.”⠀In 2017 Thai actress and runner @rachwinwong ran across Thailand to raise funds for needy hospitals. The epic 2000 km journey helped her discover her power and strength. Now she‘s going even further by running to inspire young women and show them the possibilities of their own potential.

As one of the most competitive players on the team Toña has been bringing her fierce spirit to Carta Blanca since 1961. ⠀⠀She’s a P.E. teacher who loves inspiring others to play basketball at every age and is extremely passionate about helping the next generations of Carta Blanca. “We’re going to tell them how to warm up” she says. “We are going to teach them individual techniques and group techniques and let them know they can always count on us.”⠀Watch the full story in our IGTV.📷: @asdavidelliott

Meet one of the women proving the only number that really matters is the one on your jersey.⠀At 85 Conchis is the eldest member of Carta Blanca—a basketball team from Orizaba Mexico that has been going strong since 1952. For her the team is family. “Basketball is a passion and I feel rich because I have all of my teammates” she says. “I am here thanks to my first family and them my second family.” She’s dedicated her life to basketball as a player and a coach and has four basketball hoops set up in her backyard to teach younger generations of boys and girls the true power of sport.⠀Watch the full story in our IGTV.📷: @asdavidelliott

Adela (left) has been a fierce and unstoppable athlete her whole life and she has the trophies and medals to prove it having represented Mexico internationally. She’s still going.⠀One of the founding members of Carta Blanca Adela has played with the team for 67 years. “When we started to play we would get together in primary school—we were probably 12 years old” she says. “And now we are still together and I’m 78 years old.”⠀Watch the full story in our IGTV. 📷: @asdavidelliott

Team Carta Blanca Est. 1952⠀In Orizaba Mexico there’s a team of basketball players also known as Hoops Abuelas who continue to confound others’ expectations. “We’re united thanks to basketball” says Lulu. Playing together for nearly seven decades these women bring fire and passion to life on and off the court.⠀Watch the full story in our IGTV.📷: @asdavidelliott

⠀⠀Founded in 1952 in Orizaba Mexico team Carta Blanca’s players have been defying stereotypes about women and sports for as long as they can remember. For almost seven decades these women have slipped on their canary yellow jerseys and cast giant shadows on the basketball court. They’re revolutionaries in their community an extended family of strong women who laugh cry and play sport together every day. For these amazing women family is the teammate who reaches out a hand when legs give out on the court or who delivers a competitive shove in the paint because they know—even at 70-plus—they can handle it. ⠀📽️: @changeme2012Thank you to the amazing women of team Carta Blanca.

“Give it your 100% you never know how far that can take you.”⠀After watching the London 2012 games English sprinter Sophie Hahn was inspired to take up athletics. Just a year later she was already a world record holder and well on her way to taking gold in all four major para athletics competitions. “Sneakers are the ideal canvases to give people access to art.”⠀Growing up in South Africa Karabo Poppy was obsessed with art but could rarely find herself or her experiences reflected in it. She found an exception in the barbershops and salons of Johannesburg. Her love for art grew around the colorful hand-painted signage the bold typography and the profiles of people with different hair styles lining the walls. Her goal is to make art both accessible and functional which is why she’s chosen the Air Force 1 as her ideal canvas. To say we love Karabo’s take on our classic shoe would be an understatement. Check out our story to learn why we partnered with @karabo_poppy and the places that inspired her iconic #NikeByYou work.
